Counts: first dorsal-fin rays II,9; pectoral-fin rays i19–i21; pelvic-fin rays 13; gill rakers on first arch (outer/inner) 8–9/10, on second arch 9/11; longitudinal scales 36; transverse scale rows below first dorsal-fin origin 10, below first dorsal-fin midbase 7.5, below second dorsal-fin origin 7.5, above anal-fin origin 25.5.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3F070329FF2186E5DA4AC0A1FA62781F" blockId="247.[810,1452,308,2070]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">The following measurements are in % of HL, followed by those in % of PRL in parentheses: snout length 30 (41); orbit diameter 28 (39); postorbital length 46 (64); postrostral length 73; orbit–preopercle distance 39 (53); suborbital width 15 (21); upper-jaw length 30 (41); length of rictus 24 (33); length of premaxillary tooth band 18 (24); preoral length 25 (34); distance between tip and lateral angle of snout 18 (25); snout width 27 (37); internasal width 21 (29); interorbital width 21 (29); body width over pectoral-fin bases 57 (78); body depth at first dorsal-fin origin 82 (112); body depth at anal-fin origin 69 (95); prepelvic length 116 (160); preanus length 135 (185); preanal length 153 (210); isthmus–pelvic distance 38 (52); isthmus–anus distance 57 (78); isthmus–anal distance 74 (101); pelvic–anal distance 42 (58); anusanal distance 18 (25); pelvic-fin length 44 (60); pectoralfin length 50 (68); predorsal length 115 (158); height of first dorsal fin 99 (135); length of first dorsal-fin base 26 (36); interdorsal length 35 (49); length of gill slit 14 (19); length of posterior nostril 4 (5); barbel length 12 (16).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3F070329FF2186E5DA4AC719FB6B7879" blockId="247.[810,1452,308,2070]" box="[863,1164,1329,1356]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2186E5DA4AC719FC71787E" bold="true" box="[863,918,1329,1355]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Size.</emphasis>
To at least 
<quantity id="F840AECCFF2186E5DD02C719FBBB7879" box="[1047,1116,1329,1356]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" unit="cm" value="35.0">35 cm</quantity>
TL.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="77A250A2FF2186E5DA4AC77BFAD178A5" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="3F070329FF2186E5DA4AC77BFAD178A5" blockId="247.[810,1452,308,2070]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2186E5DA4AC77BFC1E7858" bold="true" box="[863,1017,1363,1389]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Distribution.</emphasis>
So far known only from Sagami Bay (Appendix 3-10B). Depth unknown. Very rare.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="77A250A2FF2186EBDA4AC7B0FF127E1E" lastPageId="249" lastPageNumber="250" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3F070329FF2186E5DA4AC7B0FBEA7BAA" blockId="247.[810,1452,308,2070]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2186E5DA4AC7B0FC347887" bold="true" box="[863,979,1432,1458]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Remarks.</emphasis>
For a full description see the original description given by 
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF2186E5DD5BC791FACC78E1" author="Okamura, O." box="[1102,1323,1465,1492]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" refId="ref297275" refString="Okamura, O. (1970 a) Fauna Japonica, Macrourina (Pisces). Academic Press of Japan, Tokyo, 216 pp., 64 pls." type="book" year="1970">Okamura (1970a)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2186E5DC5CC792FC4378C0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2186E5DC5CC792FC4378C0" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Nezumia kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from a single specimen collected from Sagami Bay (
<figureCitation id="A7831FACFF2186E5DD9FC7D5FB137B2D" box="[1162,1268,1533,1560]" captionStart="FIGURE 166" captionStartId="248.[136,235,855,879]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,159,816]" captionTargetId="figure-223@248.[151,1436,156,819]" captionTargetPageId="248" captionText="FIGURE 166. Holotype of Nezumia kamoharai. BSKU 14202, 62.4 mm HL, 350+ mm TL, Sagami Bay, Pacific. (A) Lateral view; (B) dorsal and (C) ventral views of the head and trunk. Preserved condition. [Photos: N. Nakayama]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6423144" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6423144/files/figure.png" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Fig. 166</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="E003BD8BFF2186E5DC5CC7D5FA4C7B22" box="[1353,1451,1533,1559]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">holotype</typeStatus>
is the only representative of this rare species and, despite intensive sampling efforts in southern 
<collectingCountry id="47AF43B9FF2186E5DC71C46AFA407B69" box="[1380,1447,1602,1628]" name="Japan" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Japan</collectingCountry>
, no additional specimens have been collected since the original description.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3F070329FF2186EADA4AC48FFDDC7A59" blockId="247.[810,1452,308,2070]" lastBlockId="248.[136,778,1669,2070]" lastPageId="248" lastPageNumber="249" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2186E5DA4AC48FFAC77BF4" bold="true" box="[863,1312,1703,1730]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Relationships and comparisons.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2186E5DC5CC480FC447BD6" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2186E5DC5CC480FC447BD6" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Nezumia kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unlikely to be confused with any other Japanese congeners in having 13 pelvic-fin rays, a moderately long, pointed snout (30% HL), and the middle row of body-scale spinules distinctly enlarged compared with adjacent rows (
<figureCitation id="A7831FACFF2186E5DD08C57AFB627A59" box="[1053,1157,1873,1900]" captionStart="FIGURE 167" captionStartId="248.[136,235,1535,1559]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,989,1499]" captionTargetId="figure-264@248.[151,1436,989,1499]" captionTargetPageId="248" captionText="FIGURE 167. Scanning electron micrographs showing body scale (from the dorsum below the interdorsal space) of Nezumia kamoharai. BSKU 14202, holotype, 62.4 mm HL. (A) View from above; (B) oblique view. [Photos: NSMT]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6423146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6423146/files/figure.png" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Fig. 167</figureCitation>
). Elsewhere, this species appears to be most closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2186E5DDFBC55CFBD47A85" authority="(Roule &amp; Angel, 1933)" baseAuthorityName="Roule &amp; Angel" baseAuthorityYear="1933" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="longebarbata">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2186E5DDFBC55CFA4C7ABB" box="[1262,1451,1908,1934]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">N. longebarbata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF2186E5DA24C5BEFBCC7A85" author="Roule, L. &amp; Angel, F." box="[817,1067,1942,1968]" pageId="247" pageNumber="248" pagination="1 - 115" refId="ref298577" refString="Roule, L. &amp; Angel, F. (1933) Poissons provenant des campagnes du Prince Albert Ier de Monaco. Resultats des Campagnes Scientifiques Accomplies sur son Yacht par Albert 1 er Monaco, fasc. 86, 1 - 115 (+ 1 - 4), pls. I-IV." type="book chapter" year="1933">Roule &amp; Angel, 1933</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
so far known from Madeira and the 
<collectingRegion id="FD7CCDCBFF2186E5DA47C590FC627AE7" box="[850,901,1976,2002]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Gulf" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Gulf</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingRegion id="FD7CCDCBFF2186E5DABFC590FBE47AE7" box="[938,1027,1976,2002]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="247" pageNumber="248">Mexico</collectingRegion>
. These two species are similar to each other in having 13 pelvic-fin rays and the underside of the head broadly naked from the snout tip to a vertical at the hind rim of the orbit. However, 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2E86EAD8FDC4AEFD667BAA" box="[488,641,1669,1695]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EAD8FDC4AEFD667BAA" box="[488,641,1669,1695]" italics="true" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">N. kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is separable from 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2E86EAD9D0C480FE9A7BF4" baseAuthorityName="Roule &amp; Angel" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[197,381,1703,1729]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="longebarbata">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EAD9D0C480FE9A7BF4" box="[197,381,1703,1729]" italics="true" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">N. longebarbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a smaller orbit (28% HL vs. 31–32%), shorter barbel (12% HL vs. 17–23%) and pectoral fin (50% HL vs. 53–57%), and slightly larger body scales (transverse scale rows below the second dorsal-fin origin 7.5 vs. 8.8). [Data for 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2E86EADB45C518FCED7A7C" baseAuthorityName="Roule &amp; Angel" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[592,778,1839,1865]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="longebarbata">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EADB45C518FCED7A7C" box="[592,778,1839,1865]" italics="true" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">N. longebarbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are from 
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF2E86EAD9FAC57AFDD67A59" author="Marshall, N. B. &amp; Iwamoto, T." box="[239,561,1873,1900]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" pagination="624 - 649" refId="ref293188" refString="Marshall, N. B. &amp; Iwamoto, T. (1973) Family Macrouridae [in part: Cynomacrurus, Odontomacrurus, Coelorhynchus, Coryphaenoides, Hymenocephalus, and Nezumia]. In: Cohen, D. M. (Ed.), Fishes of the Western North Atlantic, Part 6. Sears Foundation for Marine Research, Yale University, New Haven, pp. 496 - 515, 530 - 563, 565 - 580, 601 - 612, 624 - 649." type="journal article" year="1973">Marshall &amp; Iwamoto (1973)</bibRefCitation>
.]
</paragraph>
<caption id="6BC753A1FF2E86EAD99DC17FFB987EA4" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6423144" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6423144" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6423144/files/figure.png" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" startId="248.[136,235,855,879]" targetBox="[151,1436,159,816]" targetPageId="248">
<paragraph id="3F070329FF2E86EAD99DC17FFB987EA4" blockId="248.[136,1451,855,913]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EAD99DC17FFEFB7E5A" bold="true" box="[136,284,855,879]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">FIGURE 166.</emphasis>
Holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2E86EAD8B5C170FD8B7E5A" box="[416,620,855,879]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EAD8B5C170FD8B7E5A" box="[416,620,855,879]" italics="true" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">Nezumia kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. BSKU 14202, 62.4 mm HL, 350+ mm TL, Sagami Bay, Pacific. (A) Lateral view; (B) dorsal and (C) ventral views of the head and trunk. Preserved condition. [Photos: N. Nakayama]
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="6BC753A1FF2E86EAD99DC7D7FB347B0C" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6423146" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6423146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6423146/files/figure.png" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" startId="248.[136,235,1535,1559]" targetBox="[151,1436,989,1499]" targetPageId="248">
<paragraph id="3F070329FF2E86EAD99DC7D7FB347B0C" blockId="248.[136,1452,1535,1593]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EAD99DC7D7FEC77B22" bold="true" box="[136,288,1535,1559]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">FIGURE 167.</emphasis>
Scanning electron micrographs showing body scale (from the dorsum below the interdorsal space) of 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2E86EADC46C428FF117B0C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EADC46C428FF117B0C" italics="true" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">Nezumia kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. BSKU 14202, holotype, 62.4 mm HL. (A) View from above; (B) oblique view. [Photos: NSMT]
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="3F070329FF2E86EBD9A8C55CFF127E1E" blockId="248.[136,778,1669,2070]" lastBlockId="249.[136,778,173,811]" lastPageId="249" lastPageNumber="250" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">
In his visit to BSKU in 2009, T. Iwamoto (CAS) informed the present author that 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2E86EAD8E4C5BEFD6D7A85" box="[497,650,1942,1968]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EAD8E4C5BEFD6D7A85" box="[497,650,1942,1968]" italics="true" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">N. kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also shares many features with 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2E86EAD865C590FD5F7AE7" authority="(Gilbert, 1905)" baseAuthorityName="Gilbert" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[368,696,1975,2002]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obliquata">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EAD865C590FE187AE7" box="[368,511,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">N. obliquata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF2E86EADB07C590FD487AE7" author="Gilbert, C. H." box="[530,687,1975,2002]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" pagination="573 - 713" refId="ref285669" refString="Gilbert, C. H. (1905) The deep-sea fishes of the Hawaiian Islands. In: Jordan, D. S. &amp; Evermann, B. W. (Eds.), The Aquatic Resources of the Hawaiian Islands. Bulletin of the U. S. Fish Commission, 23. Government Printing Office, Washington DC, pp. 573 - 713, figs. 230 - 276, pls. 66 - 101. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 12624" type="book chapter" year="1905">Gilbert, 1905</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, a rare species confined to the Hawaiian-Emperor Seamount Chain. The latter species was originally described from a small juvenile collected from 
<collectingRegion id="FD7CCDCBFF2E86EADD8BC4ADFB087BAA" box="[1182,1263,1669,1695]" country="United States of America" name="Hawaii" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">Hawaii</collectingRegion>
[USNM 51514, 
<typeStatus id="E003BD8BFF2E86EADA3FC48FFC6B7BF4" box="[810,908,1703,1729]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">holotype</typeStatus>
(ca. 
<quantity id="F840AECCFF2E86EADAD9C480FBC77BF7" box="[972,1056,1704,1730]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" unit="mm" value="24.0">24 mm</quantity>
HL, 127+ mm TL, fide 
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF2E86EADC5EC480FC7E7BD1" author="Sazonov, Y. I." pageId="248" pageNumber="249" pagination="149 - 160" refId="ref298922" refString="Sazonov, Y. I. (1994) Additions to the list of macrourids (Gadiformes, Bathygadidae, and Macrouridae) from the Northwest Pacific Ridge. Journal of Ichthyology, 34, 98 - 115. [Originally published in Russian in Voprosy Ikhtiologii, 34, 149 - 160.]" type="journal article" year="1994">Sazonov 1994:103</bibRefCitation>
)], and is poorly represented in museum collections. 
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF2E86EADAAAC4C4FB987A33" author="Sazonov, Y. I." box="[959,1151,1772,1798]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" pagination="149 - 160" refId="ref298922" refString="Sazonov, Y. I. (1994) Additions to the list of macrourids (Gadiformes, Bathygadidae, and Macrouridae) from the Northwest Pacific Ridge. Journal of Ichthyology, 34, 98 - 115. [Originally published in Russian in Voprosy Ikhtiologii, 34, 149 - 160.]" type="journal article" year="1994">Sazonov (1994)</bibRefCitation>
recorded an additional specimen of this species from Ojin Guyot in the Emperor Seamounts (ZMMGU P.18245, 
<quantity id="F840AECCFF2E86EADD82C507FB1A7A7F" box="[1175,1277,1839,1866]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.06" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" unit="mm" value="60.6">60.6 mm</quantity>
HL, 398+ mm TL), although he considered his identification tentative due to a number of differences related to the difference in body size between the 
<typeStatus id="E003BD8BFF2E86EADD33C5BEFB6F7A85" box="[1062,1160,1942,1968]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">holotype</typeStatus>
and the second specimen. An examination of Sazonov’s (1994) specimen revealed its close similarity with 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2E86EADD57C5F2FB387AC1" box="[1090,1247,2010,2036]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EADD57C5F2FB387AC1" box="[1090,1247,2010,2036]" italics="true" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">N. kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the 
<typeStatus id="E003BD8BFF2E86EADC5CC5F2FA4C7AC1" box="[1353,1451,2010,2036]" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2E86EADA58C5D4FC0B7523" box="[845,1004,2044,2070]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="248" pageNumber="249" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2E86EADA58C5D4FC0B7523" box="[845,1004,2044,2070]" italics="true" pageId="248" pageNumber="249">N. kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from that specimen in having shorter barbel (12% HL vs. 17%), pelvic fin (44% HL vs. 65%), and pectoral fin (50% HL vs. 59%). Spinulation of the body scales is also different between the two specimens. In the 
<typeStatus id="E003BD8BFF2F86EBD84CC33BFE5C7C18" box="[345,443,275,301]" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2F86EBD8F1C33CFD677C18" box="[484,640,275,301]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2F86EBD8F1C33CFD677C18" box="[484,640,275,301]" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">N. kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the middle row of spinules is distinctly larger than adjacent rows (
<figureCitation id="A7831FACFF2F86EBD985C37FFF147C47" box="[144,243,343,370]" captionStart="FIGURE 167" captionStartId="248.[136,235,1535,1559]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,989,1499]" captionTargetId="figure-264@248.[151,1436,989,1499]" captionTargetPageId="248" captionText="FIGURE 167. Scanning electron micrographs showing body scale (from the dorsum below the interdorsal space) of Nezumia kamoharai. BSKU 14202, holotype, 62.4 mm HL. (A) View from above; (B) oblique view. [Photos: NSMT]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6423146" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6423146/files/figure.png" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">Fig. 167</figureCitation>
), whereas in the “ 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2F86EBD8D5C370FDAA7C44" baseAuthorityName="Gilbert" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[448,589,343,369]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obliquata">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2F86EBD8D5C370FDAA7C44" box="[448,589,343,369]" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">N. obliquata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” specimen from the Emperor Seamounts, the middle row is not especially enlarged (
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF2F86EBD9EEC3B3FE427C80" author="Sazonov, Y. I." box="[251,421,411,437]" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" pagination="149 - 160" refId="ref298922" refString="Sazonov, Y. I. (1994) Additions to the list of macrourids (Gadiformes, Bathygadidae, and Macrouridae) from the Northwest Pacific Ridge. Journal of Ichthyology, 34, 98 - 115. [Originally published in Russian in Voprosy Ikhtiologii, 34, 149 - 160.]" type="journal article" year="1994">Sazonov 1994</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 3). These two specimens are almost equal in size, and their differences appear to warrant specific separation. The status of Sazonov’s (1994) specimen is still uncertain, but it does not seem to represent either 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2F86EBD84EC00CFE007F08" baseAuthorityName="Gilbert" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[347,487,547,573]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obliquata">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2F86EBD84EC00CFE007F08" box="[347,487,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">N. obliquata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nor 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2F86EBDB09C00CFD517F08" box="[540,694,547,573]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2F86EBDB09C00CFD517F08" box="[540,694,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">N. kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Based on the original description given by 
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF2F86EBDB27C06DFD3F7F55" author="Gilbert, C. H." box="[562,728,581,608]" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" pagination="573 - 713" refId="ref285669" refString="Gilbert, C. H. (1905) The deep-sea fishes of the Hawaiian Islands. In: Jordan, D. S. &amp; Evermann, B. W. (Eds.), The Aquatic Resources of the Hawaiian Islands. Bulletin of the U. S. Fish Commission, 23. Government Printing Office, Washington DC, pp. 573 - 713, figs. 230 - 276, pls. 66 - 101. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 12624" type="book chapter" year="1905">Gilbert (1905)</bibRefCitation>
, the 
<typeStatus id="E003BD8BFF2F86EBD99DC04FFF0D7FB4" box="[136,234,615,641]" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2F86EBD80DC040FE4F7FB4" baseAuthorityName="Gilbert" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[280,424,615,641]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obliquata">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2F86EBD80DC040FE4F7FB4" box="[280,424,615,641]" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">N. obliquata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF2F86EBDB5FC040FD0F7FB4" box="[586,744,615,641]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Nezumia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="249" pageNumber="250" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF2F86EBDB5FC040FD0F7FB4" box="[586,744,615,641]" italics="true" pageId="249" pageNumber="250">N. kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having fewer pelvic-fin rays (12 vs. 13) and smaller body scales (9 below the second dorsal-fin origin vs. 7.5). To resolve the taxonomic status of these species, a further study should be done when more specimens become available.
</paragraph>
